  # Why: The whole feature exists to flip the live runtime path off the
  # Phase-0 single-LLM shortcut and onto the orchestrator. This is the
  # end-to-end shape the demo gate (AC-DEMO-01.2) consumes.
  @task:TASK-LCA-005
  @key-example @smoke
  Scenario: A learner turn returns the Phase-1 metadata shape
    Given the MCP server has booted with a working orchestrator_factory
    And a tutoring session is active for a learner on a planned topic
    When the learner sends a turn message via the MCP tutor_turn tool
    Then the response should include a tutor_response for the learner
    # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=high] Phase-1 decision strings: accept | exhausted | fallback
    And the response should include a decision of accept, exhausted, or fallback
    And the response should include the number of revision attempts taken
    And the response should indicate whether the turn was flagged for review
    And the response should include the duration the turn took to produce

  # Why: Per-turn factory isolation is the single most load-bearing
  # invariant for concurrent sessions; closure-capture bugs would silently
  # cross-contaminate Coach observations between learners.
  @task:TASK-LCA-005
  @key-example @smoke @invariant
  Scenario: Each turn is served by a freshly-constructed orchestrator
    Given the MCP server has booted with a working orchestrator_factory
    And two distinct tutoring sessions are active for two different learners
    When both sessions send a turn at the same time
    Then each turn should be served by its own orchestrator instance
    And no Coach observation from one session should appear in the other
      session's verdict path

  # Why: The Player adapter is the simpler of the two — it must round-trip
  # the learner message through the configured LLM with the role prompt as
  # system context, with no transformation.
  @task:TASK-LCA-001
  @key-example
  Scenario: The Player adapter responds by delegating to its LLM client
    Given an LLMPlayerAdapter wrapping the configured Player LLM
    And the Player role prompt has been loaded from
      roles/tutor/prompts/player.md
    When the orchestrator asks the Player to respond to a learner message
    Then the Player role prompt should be supplied as the system context
    And the learner message should be supplied as the user prompt
    And the response should be returned to the orchestrator unchanged

  # Why: The Coach adapter completes the loop — it must call its LLM,
  # validate the JSON, and surface a CoachVerdict the orchestrator can act on.
  @task:TASK-LCA-002
  @key-example @smoke
  Scenario: The Coach adapter returns a fully-shaped verdict for a valid response
    # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=high] Coach role prompt lives at
    # roles/tutor/prompts/coach.md and is loaded via RoleConfig.load_coach_prompt()
    Given an LLMCoachAdapter configured against the Coach LLM provider
    And the Coach role prompt has been loaded from roles/tutor/prompts/coach.md
    When the orchestrator asks the Coach to evaluate a Player response
    And the Coach LLM returns valid per-criterion JSON
    Then a CoachVerdict should be returned with a score for every rubric
      criterion
    # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=high] Per-criterion and weighted scores live in [0.0, 1.0]
    And the verdict should include a weighted total within [0.0, 1.0]
    And the verdict should include a decision of accept or revise
    And any misconceptions in the verdict should be dispatched fire-and-forget

  # Why: The Player revision prompt is the security boundary for ASSUM-008 —
  # only structured rubric feedback may cross from Coach to Player.
  @task:TASK-LCA-001
  @key-example
  Scenario: The Player adapter assembles a structured revision prompt
    Given the Coach has returned rubric feedback for two below-threshold
      criteria
    When the orchestrator asks the Player to revise its previous response
    Then the assembled revision prompt should contain the original learner
      message
    And it should contain the previous Player response
    # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=medium] Revision prompt carries criterion_id and
    # target_score only; suggested_focus is excluded so the structured-only
    # invariant (ASSUM-008) is trivially auditable
    And it should contain each below-threshold criterion id with its target
      score
    And the revised response should be returned to the orchestrator unchanged

  # ==========================================================================
  # GROUP B: Boundary Conditions
  # ==========================================================================

  # Why: Per-criterion scores at the exact clamp boundaries are accepted as-is
  # by the deterministic post-processor (Path C). Just-outside is clamped.
  @task:TASK-LCA-002
  @boundary
  Scenario Outline: Per-criterion scores at and inside the clamp boundary are accepted
    Given an LLMCoachAdapter and a Coach LLM that emits valid per-criterion JSON
    When the Coach LLM returns a per-criterion score of <score>
    Then the resulting verdict should record the criterion score as <recorded>

    Examples:
      | score | recorded |
      | 0.0   | 0.0      |
      | 0.001 | 0.001    |
      | 0.5   | 0.5      |
      | 0.999 | 0.999    |
      | 1.0   | 1.0      |

  # Why: Just-outside the [0.0, 1.0] range — the deterministic post-processor
  # must clamp rather than reject, so a single rogue score does not push the
  # whole turn into fallback.
  @task:TASK-LCA-002
  @boundary
  Scenario Outline: Per-criterion scores outside the clamp boundary are clamped
    Given an LLMCoachAdapter and a Coach LLM that emits valid JSON shape
    When the Coach LLM returns a per-criterion score of <score>
    Then the resulting verdict should record the criterion score as <recorded>

    Examples:
      | score | recorded |
      | -0.1  | 0.0      |
      | 1.1   | 1.0      |

  # Why: The orchestrator's max_revision_attempts contract is bounded; the
  # adapters must support exactly that many revise() calls per turn and no
  # more (the orchestrator enforces, but the adapter must not crash at the
  # configured limit).
  # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=high] max_revision_attempts default is 3 per
  # FEAT-PH1-003.1 (cited in features/deepagents-tutoring-loop/)
  @task:TASK-LCA-001
  @boundary
  Scenario: The Player adapter handles the maximum configured revision attempts
    Given an orchestrator configured with max_revision_attempts of 3
    And every Coach evaluation returns below the acceptance threshold
    When the orchestrator runs a turn to exhaustion
    Then the Player adapter should be asked to revise exactly 3 times
    And the final decision should be exhausted

  # Why: SessionState minimum-required fields — adapters must run with the
