  # Why: parse_coach_output's behaviour on extra/unknown criteria is a real
  # design choice — locking it down here prevents drift when the rubric
  # evolves in Phase-2.
  # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=medium] Extra unknown criteria are silently
  # discarded; only the six Phase-1 rubric criteria are read into the verdict
  @task:TASK-LCA-002
  @edge-case @integration
  Scenario: Coach JSON with extra unknown criteria is accepted with the extras ignored
    Given the Coach LLM returns JSON containing the six Phase-1 rubric criteria
      plus an additional unknown criterion "vibes_alignment"
    When the orchestrator asks the Coach to evaluate a Player response
    Then a fully-shaped CoachVerdict should be returned
    And the verdict should contain only the six Phase-1 rubric criteria
    And the unknown criterion should be silently discarded

  # Why: latency_budget_seconds is enforced by the orchestrator, not the
  # adapters — but a slow Coach LLM call must surface as a budget exhaustion,
  # not a Coach error, so the on_flag callback fires correctly.
  @task:TASK-LCA-005
  @edge-case @integration
  Scenario: A Coach evaluation exceeding the latency budget is reported as over-budget
    Given an orchestrator with a configured latency_budget_seconds
    And a Coach LLM that takes longer than the budget to respond
    When the orchestrator runs a turn
    Then the turn should be flagged for review with reason "over-budget"
    And the on_flag callback should fire with the over-budget reason
    And the Coach adapter should not be reported as unavailable

  # Why: Snapshot semantics for env vars resolved at boot — operators
  # rotating AGENT_MODELS__COACH_MODEL after boot must understand they need
  # to restart the server. This is a documentation invariant as much as code.
  # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=medium] AGENT_MODELS__* env vars are resolved once
  # at MCPAdapter.__init__; rotation post-boot has no effect until restart
  @task:TASK-LCA-004
  @edge-case @integration @invariant
  Scenario: Env var rotation post-boot does not change the resolved Coach provider
    Given the MCP server has booted with AGENT_MODELS__COACH_MODEL set to
      provider X
    When AGENT_MODELS__COACH_MODEL is changed to provider Y in the environment
    And a new tutor_turn is invoked on an already-active session
    Then the Coach evaluation should still be served by provider X
    And no warning or error should be raised for the env change alone
